Currently, serving static dist files uses hardcoded options (no index, 1 year expire time). This PR allows to pass custom options, using exactly the same syntax as one can already pass custom options for serving static files under static/.
For example, this will set CORS header for dist files:
// nuxt.config.js

module.exports = {
  render: {
    dist: {
      setHeaders (res, path) {
        res.setHeader('Access-Control-Allow-Origin', '*')
      },
    },
  },
}

As a continuation to previous works on splitPages, this PR makes both optimization (webpack 4 option) and splitChunks fully customizable.
We can disable all splitting features using this option in nuxt.config.js:
build: {
    optimization: {
      splitChunks: {
        chunks: 'async',
      }
    },
    splitChunks: {
      pages: false,
      vendor: false,
      commons: false,
      runtime: false,
      layouts: false
    },
}
Other improvements with this PR

Splitting for layout chunks disabled by default for performance
shouldPrefetch is falsy by default to improve TTL
resourcHints are disabled for dev mode

SPA Improvements

Support render.shouldPrefetch and render.shouldPreload
Disabled loadingIndicator to improve TTL
Runtime chunk is inlined only for production

This update is just to allow the router to be generated by an asynchronous function. A fairly common requirement. This would mainly be needed for special implementations of the router module, but since the router is built so early in the lifecycle it makes it hard to route properly if you need the API to define the routes for the app in some way (like a wordpress backend).
nuxt-community/router-module#4
My implementation may be improved as I am not familiar enough with the codebase to be confident in it, the update is meant to open up the discussion on it. To me this update is extremely simple and should not cause any problems in nuxt, at least I have not seen any errors associated with the update in my own testing (I edited directly out of node_modules then applied the update to this fork, since this functionality is a requirement in the project I am working on).
Thoughts? The idea here does not need to be merged, more just to show a simple way to allow API driven routing.
Here is an example of, if using the router module how you can use the router.js file with this update.
export async function createRouter(options) {
    // since the axios module has not been initialized yet it needs to be included manually
    const response = await axios.get(process.env.API_URL + '/wp/v2/menus')
    console.log(response.data)
    const routes = []
    //loop response and build route array
    return new Router({
        mode: 'history',
        routes: routes
    })
}

